Dockerfile
md2man\-all.sh
\f[]
.fi
.SH Generating man pages from the Markdown files
.PP
The recommended approach for generating the man pages is via a Docker
container.
Using the supplied Dockerfile, Docker will create a Fedora based
container and isolate the Pandoc installation.
This is a seamless process, saving you from dealing with Pandoc and
dependencies on your own computer.
.SS Building the Fedora / Pandoc image
.PP
There is a Dockerfile provided in the \f[C]docker/contrib/man/md\f[]
directory.
.PP
Using this Dockerfile, create a Docker image tagged
\f[C]fedora/pandoc\f[]:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
docker\ build\ \ \-t\ fedora/pandoc\ .
\f[]
.fi
.SS Utilizing the Fedora / Pandoc image
.PP
Once the image is built, run a container using the image with
\f[I]volumes\f[]:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
docker\ run\ \-v\ /<path\-to\-git\-dir>/docker/contrib/man:/pandoc:rw\ \\
\-w\ /pandoc\ \-i\ fedora/pandoc\ /pandoc/md/md2man\-all.sh
\f[]
.fi
.PP
The Pandoc Docker container will process the Markdown files and generate
the man pages inside the \f[C]docker/contrib/man/man1\f[] directory
using Docker volumes.
For more information on Docker volumes see the man page for
\f[C]docker\ run\f[] and also look at the article [Sharing Directories
via Volumes] (http://docs.docker.io/use/working_with_volumes/).
